VITE_MAKE_WEBHOOK_URL=https://hook.eu1.make.com/YOUR_WEBHOOK_ID_HERE
```

Right now, leave it exactly like that as a placeholder. You'll replace `YOUR_WEBHOOK_ID_HERE` with the real URL once you build the Make.com scenario in the next step.

**Important:** Vite requires env variables to start with `VITE_` or the app can't read them. That prefix is why it's named that way.

---

## Step 3 — Add `.env` to `.gitignore`

If you use Git (and you should), make sure `.env` is listed in your `.gitignore` file so it never gets pushed to GitHub. Open `.gitignore` and check — it almost certainly already has this line, but verify:
```
.env
```

---

## Step 4 — Restart your dev server

After creating the `.env` file, **stop and restart** `npm run dev`. Vite only reads env variables on startup, so a restart is required for it to pick up the new value.

---

## The order of everything end-to-end
```
1. Replace App.tsx          ← you're doing this now
2. Create .env              ← placeholder URL for now
3. Build Make.com scenario  ← this gives you the real webhook URL
4. Paste real URL into .env ← swap out the placeholder
5. Restart dev server       ← npm run dev
6. Deploy to Netlify        ← add the env var there too (see below)